import numpy as np

def plot_timeseries(x, y, title):
    trace = go.Scatter(x = x, y = y, name = title, marker=dict(color="#FF7800"))
    
    layout = go.Layout(title=title)
    fig = go.Figure(data=[trace], layout=layout)
    py.iplot(fig)
    
    return trace

n = 400
x2 = np.linspace(0, n-1, num = n)

constant = np.repeat(1,n)
linear = 2*x2
constant_with_noise = constant.copy()
constant_with_periodical_noise = constant.copy()
constant_with_noise[[69, 150, 230, 169, 269]] = 2
constant_with_periodical_noise[::100] = 2

fig.append_trace(plot_timeseries(x2,constant,"Constant"), 1,1)

fig.append_trace(plot_timeseries(x2, linear, "Linear"), 1,2)

fig.append_trace(plot_timeseries(x2, constant_with_noise,"Constant with random noise"), 1,3)

fig.append_trace(plot_timeseries(x2, constant_with_periodical_noise,"Constant with periodical noise"), 1,4)

x1 = np.linspace(0, 10*np.pi, num = n)

sinus = np.sin(x1) + 2.5
noisy_sinus = sinus + np.random.rand(len(x1)) + np.linspace(0, 1.5, num = n)
more_noisy_sinus = sinus + 3*(np.random.rand(len(x1)) - 0.5)

k = 20
ind = np.random.choice(n, k, replace=False)
somewhere_noisy_sinus = sinus + (np.random.rand(len(x1)) - 0.5)/2 
somewhere_noisy_sinus[ind] += 4 * (np.random.rand(k) - 0.5)

fig.append_trace(plot_timeseries(x1,sinus, "Sinus"), 2,1)

fig.append_trace(plot_timeseries(x1,noisy_sinus, "Slightly noisy sinus"), 2,2)

fig.append_trace(plot_timeseries(x1,more_noisy_sinus, "Noisy sinus"), 2,3)

fig.append_trace(plot_timeseries(x1,somewhere_noisy_sinus, "Somewhere noisy sinus"), 2,4)

def plot_predictions(x, y, pred, k, title):
    trace1 = go.Scatter(x = x, y = y, name = f"Real values", marker=dict(color="#FF7800"))
    trace2 = go.Scatter(x = x[k:], y = pred, name = f"Predicted values", marker=dict(color="#2D364C"))

    layout = go.Layout(title=title)
    fig = go.Figure(data=[trace1, trace2], layout=layout)
    py.iplot(fig)
    
    #return pred

k = 30

def pred_naive(timeseries, k = 30):
    return np.roll(timeseries[k:] ,1)[1:]

def moving_average(timeseries, k = 30, m = 5):
    return np.convolve(timeseries[k:], np.ones(m), 'valid') / m

def pred_exp_smooth(timeseries, k, smoothing_level = 0.2):
    n = len(timeseries)
    predictions = []
    
    for i in range(k,n):
        model = SimpleExpSmoothing(timeseries[:i])
        fit = model.fit(smoothing_level=smoothing_level)

        predictions.extend(fit.forecast(steps = 1))
        
    return np.asarray(predictions)

def plot_p_acf(y, nlags = 20, title = "", plot_thresholds = False):
    lag_acf = acf(y, nlags=nlags)
    lag_pacf = pacf(y, nlags=nlags, method='ols')
    
    trace1 = go.Scatter(x = list(range(len(lag_acf))), y = lag_acf, 
                        name = f"Autocorrelation", marker=dict(color="#FF7800"), mode = "lines+markers")
    trace2 = go.Scatter(x = list(range(len(lag_pacf))), y = lag_pacf, 
                        name = f"Partial autocorrelation", marker=dict(color="#2D364C"), mode = "lines+markers")
    trace3a = go.Scatter(x = list(range(len(lag_pacf))), y=np.repeat(-1.96/np.sqrt(len(y)),len(y)), 
                        name = f"Threshold 1", marker=dict(color="grey"), mode = "lines")
    trace3b = go.Scatter(x = list(range(len(lag_pacf))), y=np.repeat(1.96/np.sqrt(len(y)),len(y)), 
                        name = f"Threshold 2", marker=dict(color="grey"), mode = "lines")
    

    layout = go.Layout(title=f"ACF and PACF of {title}")
    if plot_thresholds:
        data=[trace1, trace2, trace3a, trace3b]
    else:
        data=[trace1, trace2]
    fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
    py.iplot(fig)
    
def STR_and_plot(x, y, title, freq):
    res = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(y, freq = freq)
    
    trace1 = go.Scatter(x = x, y = y, name = f"{title}", marker=dict(color="#FF7800"))
    trace2 = go.Scatter(x = x, y = res.resid, name = "Residuals", marker=dict(color="#6534AC"))
    trace3 = go.Scatter(x = x, y = res.seasonal, name = "Seasonal", marker=dict(color="#F5203E"))
    trace4 = go.Scatter(x = x, y = res.trend, name = "Trend", marker=dict(color="#2D364C"))
    
    fig = tools.make_subplots(rows=2, cols=2, print_grid=False)
    
    fig.append_trace(trace1, 1, 1)
    fig.append_trace(trace2, 2, 2)
    fig.append_trace(trace3, 1, 2)
    fig.append_trace(trace4, 2, 1)

    fig['layout'].update(title=f'STR decomposition of {title}') #showlegend=False, 
    py.iplot(fig) 
    

def pred_arima(timeseries, order, log = False):

    if log:
        timeseries = np.log(timeseries)
    
    model = ARIMA(timeseries, order=order)  
    pred = model.fit(disp=-1)  
        
    output = pd.Series(timeseries.iloc[0], index=timeseries.index)
    output = output.add(pred.fittedvalues.cumsum(), fill_value=0)

    return np.exp(output) if log else output

def create_train_test(timeseries, train_split, timesteps):
    dataset_train = LSTMDataset(np.asarray(timeseries)[:train_split].reshape(-1,1), timesteps=timesteps, reshape=True)
    dataset_test = LSTMDataset(np.asarray(timeseries)[train_split:].reshape(-1,1), timesteps=timesteps, reshape=True)
    
    return dataset_train, dataset_test

def train_gru(timeseries, train_split, timesteps, epochs):

    #dataset_train, dataset_test = create_train_test(timeseries, train_split, timesteps)
    dataset_train = LSTMDataset(np.asarray(timeseries)[:train_split].reshape(-1,1), timesteps=timesteps, reshape=True)
    dataset_test = LSTMDataset(np.asarray(timeseries)[train_split:].reshape(-1,1), timesteps=timesteps, reshape=True)
    
    X_train = dataset_train.get_ordered_test_batches()[0]
    y_train = dataset_train.get_ordered_test_batches()[1]

    X_test = dataset_test.get_ordered_test_batches()[0]
    y_test = dataset_test.get_ordered_test_batches()[1]
    
    LATENT_DIM = 5 # number of units in the RNN layer
    BATCH_SIZE = 32 # number of samples per mini-batch
    EPOCHS = epochs
    HORIZON = 1
    
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(GRU(LATENT_DIM, input_shape=(timesteps, 1)))
    model.add(Dense(HORIZON))
    
    model.compile(optimizer='RMSprop', loss='mse')    
    model.fit(X_train,
          y_train,
          batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
          shuffle=False,
          epochs=EPOCHS,
          verbose=0)
    model._make_predict_function()
    
    return model.predict(X_test)[:,0] * dataset_test.get_norm_coefs() #_make_predict_function


def train_lstm(timeseries, train_split, timesteps, epochs):
    dataset_train, dataset_test = create_train_test(timeseries, train_split, timesteps)
    
    model = LSTMModel()
    model.construct(
        seq_len = timesteps,
        num_features = 1,
        lstm_size = 64,
        n_layers = 1,
        learning_rate = 1e-3,
    )
    
    model.train_model(dataset_train, batch_size = 25, epochs = epochs)
    batches, y_true = dataset_test.get_ordered_test_batches()
    coef = dataset_test.get_norm_coefs()
    
    return model.predict(batches)[:,0]*coef

Preprocessing¶

  • Autocorrelation Function (ACF)

  • Partial Autocorrelation Function (PACF)

  • Measure of correlation between points separated by various time lags

  • Periodicity

plot_p_acf(noisy_sinus, nlags = 90, title = "noisy sinus")

plot_p_acf(positions, nlags = 20, title = "spotify positions")

  • STR decomposition

  • $Y(t) = S(t) + T(t) + R(t)$ (seasonal + trend + residuals)

  • Trend - rolling mean, Seasonal $S=Y-T$ for each season, residuals $R=Y-S-T$

  • Tools to eliminate seasonality, trend etc.

STR_and_plot(air_passengers.index[:], air_passengers["passengers"], "air passengers", freq = 12)

Forecasting¶

Naive¶

  • $Ŷ(t+h|t) = Y(t)$

  • Seasonal Naive

plot_predictions(x2, linear, pred_naive(linear, k = k-1), k = k, title = "Linear by naive forecasting")

plot_predictions(x1, sinus, pred_naive(sinus, k = k-1), k = k, title = "Sinus by naive forecasting")

plot_predictions(x_spotify, n_streams, pred_naive(n_streams, k = k-1), k = k, title = "Spotify streams by naive forecasting")

Moving average¶

  • $Ŷ(t+1|t) = mean${$Y(t),…,Y(t-n)$}

  • Mean of last n events

m = 5
pred_ma_linear = plot_predictions(x2, linear, moving_average(linear, k = k-m, m = m), k = k, title = "Linear by moving average forecasting")

pred_ma_sinus = plot_predictions(x1, sinus, moving_average(sinus, k = k-m, m = m), k = k, title = "Sinus by moving average forecasting")

pred_ma_n_streams = plot_predictions(x_spotify, n_streams, moving_average(n_streams, k = k-m, m = m), k = k, title = "Spotify streams by moving average forecasting")

k2 = 10
pred_ma_furniture = plot_predictions(furniture.index[:], furniture, moving_average(furniture, k = k2-m, m=m), k = k2, title = "Furniture sales by moving average forecasting")

Exponential smoothing¶

  • $Ŷ(t+h|t) = ⍺y(t) + ⍺(1-⍺)y(t-1) + ⍺(1-⍺)²y(t-2) + … , 0<⍺<1$

  • weighted average of past observations, weights decrease exponentially back in time

plot_predictions(x2, linear, pred_exp_smooth(linear, k = k, smoothing_level = 0.5), k = k, title = "Linear by exponential smoothing forecasting")

plot_predictions(x1, sinus, pred_exp_smooth(sinus, k = k, smoothing_level = 0.5), k = k, title = "Sinus by exponential smoothing forecasting")

plot_predictions(x_spotify, positions, pred_exp_smooth(positions, k = k, smoothing_level = 0.5), k = k, title = "Spotify postion by exponential smoothing forecasting")

plot_predictions(furniture.index[:], furniture, pred_exp_smooth(furniture, k = 10, smoothing_level = 0.3), k = 10, title = "Furniture sales by exponential smoothing forecasting")

plot_predictions(air_passengers.index[:], air_passengers["passengers"], pred_exp_smooth(air_passengers["passengers"], k = 10, 
                                                                                        smoothing_level = 0.3), k = 10, title = "Air passengers by exponential smoothing forecasting")

ARIMA - AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average¶

  • AR - regression of its own lagged values

  • I - differencing of observations

  • MA - regression of its lagged forecast errors

  • parameters p, d, q

  • Seasonal ARIMA

def shift_array(timeseries):
    return timeseries - np.roll(timeseries,1)

plot_p_acf(shift_array(noisy_sinus), nlags = 90, title = "shifted noisy sinus", plot_thresholds = True)

plot_p_acf(shift_array(np.log(furniture)), nlags = 30, title = "shifted furniture", plot_thresholds = True)

plot_p_acf(shift_array(np.log(air_passengers["passengers"])), nlags = 30, title = "shifted  air passengers", plot_thresholds = True)

plot_p_acf(shift_array(positions), nlags = 20, title = "shifted  spotify positions", plot_thresholds = True)

Anomaly Detection¶

  • Forecasts ready

  • How to detect outliers?

  • Difference between predictions and real values (prediction error)

  • Task: Try to find methods for anomaly detections 

def plot_anomaly_detection(pred_error, threshold, title = ""):
    k = len(pred_error)
    x = list(range(k))
    
    trace1 = go.Scatter(x = x, y = pred_error, name = f"Predictions error", marker=dict(color="#FF7800"))
    trace2 = go.Scatter(x = x, y = threshold, name = f"Threshold", marker=dict(color="#2D364C"))

    layout = go.Layout(title="")
    fig = go.Figure(data=[trace1, trace2], layout=layout)
    py.iplot(fig)

class AnomalyAggregator2:
    def __init__(self, y_true, pred, time_labels, features_names, config):
        """
        :param model: LSTM model
        :param input_data: input time series for analysis of time-series. The dimension needs to match the model's
                dimension
        :param time_labels: list of times relevant to each element of the time-series
        :param features_names: list of feature names
        :param which_dims: which dimensions to analyse and plot else ALL
        """

        config["date"] = []
        self.config = config

        y_true = np.asarray(y_true).reshape(-1, 1)
        pred = np.asarray(pred).reshape(-1, 1)

        self._features_names = features_names
        self._time_labels = time_labels  # [(self._seq_len - 1) :]
        # self.coef = coef

        self._anomaly_DT_obj = AnomalyDynamicThreshold(
            y_true=y_true, prediction=pred, config=config
        )

        self._anomaly_LSHT_obj = AnomalyLikelihoodThreshold(
            y_true=y_true, prediction=pred, config=config
        )

        self._anomaly_ZS_obj = AnomalyZScore(y_true=y_true, config=config)

        self._y_true = y_true  # * self.coef
        self._pred = pred  # * self.coef

    def visualize(self, dim, plot_thresholds=False):
        self._coordinates_of_anomalies()
        self._create_plot(i=dim, plot_thresholds=plot_thresholds)

    def get_coordinates(self):
        self._coordinates_of_anomalies()
        return self._anomaly_DT, self._anomaly_LSHT, self._anomaly_ZS

    def _coordinates_of_anomalies(self):

        self._anomaly_DT = self._anomaly_DT_obj.detect_anomalies()
        self._anomaly_LSHT = self._anomaly_LSHT_obj.detect_anomalies()
        self._anomaly_ZS = self._anomaly_ZS_obj.detect_anomalies()

    def _create_plotting_trace(self, data, name=""):
        """
        Creates a figure.
        """
        return go.Scatter(x=self._time_labels, y=data, name=name)

    def _create_anomaly_trace(self, anomaly, y_true, dim, name, symbol, color):
        """
        Creates a figure with points showing where the anomalies occured.
        """
        trace = go.Scatter(
            x=(self._time_labels[anomaly[dim]]),
            y=np.array(y_true[:, dim])[anomaly[dim]],
            name=name,
            mode="markers",
            marker=dict(symbol=symbol, size=10, color=color),
        )
        return trace

    def _evaluate_thresholds(self, i):
        """
        Creates a graph of distance of statistics to the thresholds (for DT and LSHT threshold)
        """
        dist = abs(self._y_true - self._pred)

        trace1a = self._create_plotting_trace(dist[:, i], name="Statistic")
        trace1b = self._create_plotting_trace(
            self._anomaly_DT_obj.get_threshold()[:, i], name="Threshold"
        )
        fig = {"data": [trace1a, trace1b], "layout": {"title": "Dynamic Threshold"}}

        trace2a = self._create_plotting_trace(
            self._anomaly_LSHT_obj.get_statistics()[:, i], name="Statistic"
        )
        trace2b = self._create_plotting_trace(
            self._anomaly_LSHT_obj.get_threshold()[:, i], name="Threshold"
        )
        fig2 = {"data": [trace2a, trace2b], "layout": {"title": "Long Short History"}}

        trace3a = self._create_plotting_trace(
            self._anomaly_ZS_obj.get_statistics()[:, i], name="Statistic"
        )
        trace3b = self._create_plotting_trace(
            self._anomaly_ZS_obj.get_threshold()[:, i], name="Threshold"
        )
        fig3 = {"data": [trace3a, trace3b], "layout": {"title": "Z-score"}}

        return fig, fig2, fig3

    def _create_plot(self, i, plot_thresholds):
        """
        Creates a graph of i-th component of real and predited time-series. The plot also shows the coordinates of
        anomalies.
        """
        global fig_threshold1, fig_threshold2, fig_threshold3
        plot_title = (
            f"{self._features_names}"
            #             f"{self._features_names[i][0]} in {self._features_names[i][1]}"
            #             if len(self._features_names[i]) > 1
            #             else f"{self._features_names[i][0]}"
        )

        trace1a = self._create_anomaly_trace(
            self._anomaly_DT,
            self._y_true,
            dim=i,
            name="Dynamic threshold",
            symbol="cross",
            color="blue",
        )
        trace1b = self._create_anomaly_trace(
            self._anomaly_LSHT,
            self._y_true,
            dim=i,
            name="Long-short history",
            symbol="circle",
            color="red",
        )

        trace1c = self._create_anomaly_trace(
            self._anomaly_ZS,
            self._y_true,
            dim=i,
            name="Z-score",
            symbol="triangle-up-open",
            color="black",
        )

        trace2 = self._create_plotting_trace(self._y_true[:, i], name="TRUE")
        trace3 = self._create_plotting_trace(self._pred[:, i], name="PRED")

        trace = [trace2, trace3, trace1a, trace1b]

        fig = {"data": trace, "layout": {"title": plot_title}}
        if plot_thresholds:
            fig_threshold1, fig_threshold2, fig_threshold3 = self._evaluate_thresholds(
                i
            )

        py.iplot(fig)
        if plot_thresholds:
            py.iplot(fig_threshold1)
            py.iplot(fig_threshold2)
            # py.iplot(fig_threshold3)

Dynamic Threshold¶

  • Self-adapting method analysing historic prediction errors

  • Last n prediction errors

  • m = mean of prediction error

  • v = variance of prediction error

  • T = $k_{1}$*m + $k_{2}$*v

  • Detecting sudden changes in timeseries

Grubbs test¶

  • Statistical test (Zero vs. one anomaly) in prediction error

  • Detecting one outlier at a time

Long Short History Threshold¶

  • Comparing Short-term and Long-term prediction error

  • Detecting contextual anomalies
